REASONS FOR JUDGMENT

ALTOBELLI J:

INTRODUCTION

These reasons for judgment explain the orders the Court has made about X, born in 2020 (“the child”). The child has two caring parents. Her father is the applicant (“the father”), her mother is the respondent (“the mother) (collectively “the parents”) in this matter.

BACKGROUND

Much of the background to this matter was explained in this Court’s earlier judgment in respect of the mother’s application under the Hague Convention on the Civil Aspects of International Child Abduction 1980 (“the Hague Convention proceedings”). The Court’s discussion in Bohler & Jugovac [2024] FedCFamC1F 592 (“the Hauge Convention decision”) was not subject to dispute or criticism by the parties during the final hearing and will be reproduced and slightly updated below.
The mother is a Japanese citizen, was born in Japan and moved to Australia in late 2018 on a working holiday visa. She is 38 years old and now has permanent residency in Australia. She has had limited and unstable employment in Australia, although she is a certified health professional in Japan. The father is a Country B citizen, was born in Country C and moved to Australia in 2010. He is 44 years old and now has permanent residency in Australia and has applied for Australian citizenship. It appears that he runs his own business and has a flexible work schedule.
The parties met in Sydney in April 2019, with their relationship beginning as flatmates and soon progressing to an intimate relationship. The mother fell pregnant thereafter. In early 2020 the mother returned to Japan to visit family, with the father intending to travel to Japan shortly afterwards. However, due to travel restrictions arising from the COVID-19 pandemic, the father’s flights were cancelled, and the mother was unable to return to Australia as her pregnancy had progressed. The father obtained a travel exemption and was able to travel to Japan for the birth of the child. As the parents were not married at the time of the child’s birth, the father was not permitted to have his name on the child’s birth certificate under Japanese law. The parents became engaged in Japan on 5 July 2020 but never married.
The father returned to Australia in August 2020 due to work commitments, and the mother and the child remained in Japan, before returning to Australia in May 2021. The parents then lived together with the child in a rented unit in Suburb D. Over the following months, the parents’ relationship deteriorated.
The father commenced urgent proceedings in this Court on 27 July 2021, fearing that the mother was going to abduct the child and return to Japan. The mother purchased tickets at 4.00 pm on 27 July 2021 for a flight departing for Japan the same evening. The mother and the child were prevented from boarding the flight by the Australian Federal Police, due to the child being placed on the Family Law Watchlist earlier that day.
The mother attended Suburb E Police Station on 28 July 2021 and made allegations of family violence perpetrated by the father. The father was charged with assault occasioning actual bodily harm, stalking/intimidation and common assault, and an interim Apprehended Domestic Violence Order (“ADVO”) was issued on the same day. The father was later found not guilty in relation to these charges but was placed on a conditional release order with no conviction for 18 months for breaches of the ADVO (which was also extended for two years). The mother maintains these allegations, which the father denies.
Various interim orders were made regarding the father’s time with the child throughout 2021 and 2022, many of which were made by consent. The matter first came before me for case management on 29 November 2023. On 8 April 2024 I heard the father’s Application in a Proceeding filed 24 November 2024, where orders were made permitting the father to communicate with the child’s day care and attend special events, and for the parties to advise each other of any illness or medical treatment for the child. The matter was listed for final hearing to commence on 13 May 2024, with an estimated hearing time of five days.
On 13 May 2024, the final hearing was adjourned to 3 February 2025, in circumstances where the mother in her Outline of Case Document filed 10 May 2024 sought to run her case under the Hague Convention, and the father and the Independent Children’s Lawyer were not prepared to answer this case on short notice. The mother’s threshold application pursuant to the Family Law (Child Abduction Convention) Regulations 1986 (“the Regulations”) was thus listed for defended hearing on 26 July 2024 (“the Hague Convention proceedings”). Orders were also made by consent to increase the father’s time with the child (from five hours twice per week, to 10 hours twice per week) and for this time to be unsupervised.
This Court heard the Hague Convention proceedings on 26 July 2024 and delivered judgment on 6 September 2024. The Hague Convention decision denied the mother’s application for relief, caused the mother and child to remain in the Commonwealth of Australia, and to vest this Court with jurisdiction to determine parenting arrangements for the child under the Family Law Act 1975 (Cth) (“the Act”).

Procedural history

This matter has an extensive litigation history in this Court, spanning substantive and procedural actions under the Act and the Hague Convention. To borrow the words of Gordon & Edelman JJ in R Lawyers v Mr Daily [2025] HCA 41; (2025) 99 ALJR 1504 at [85], “... the litigation is long, tortured and complex. It is hoped it is never repeated”. By virtue of this, only relevant extracts from the procedural history of this matter will be explored.
The matter first came before the Court on 27 July 2021 and was heard by Deputy Registrar Mowat. Procedural orders requiring the parents to attend Family Dispute Resolution were made.
On 28 October 2021, the matter was heard by Judicial Registrar Chayna. Orders were made requiring the parties to file fulsome documents and appointing an Independent Children’s Lawyer. Orders were also made by consent providing for the father to spend professionally supervised time with the child for two hours each Saturday and two hours each Tuesday supervised by the paternal grandparents, orders for video communication between the father and the child, and orders providing authority for the dissemination of the child’s medical records to the father.
On 2 November 2021, Senior Judicial Registrar Crawley transferred the proceedings to Division 1 of the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia citing complexities arising from international relocation.
On 15 December 2021, the matter returned to Court and was heard by Judicial Registrar Bardetta. Further consent orders were made providing for a gradually increasing regime of time between the father and the child. The father’s time with the child was to be initially supervised in its entirety, however, following 19 January 2022 the parties agree that supervision only occur during changeovers.
On 25 March 2022, the matter returned before Judicial Registrar Bardetta. A Child Impact Report was commissioned, and further consent orders were made. The consent orders provided for more significant unsupervised time between the father and the child and for the parents to do all things reasonably necessary to enrol the child in daycare.
On 2 September 2022, the matter was again heard by Judicial Registrar Bardetta. The Court was informed about criminal matters concerning the father being on foot in a Local Court (Orders 2 September 2022, notation D). As a result of this, the mother foreshadowed filing an Application in a Proceeding for the father’s time to return to being professionally supervised. Orders were made listing the matter for interim hearing, compliance and readiness hearing and providing for filing deadlines for all relevant documentation as between the parents. Consent orders were made pending an interim hearing, on a without admissions basis for the child to spend three hours of supervised time each Tuesday and Saturday with the child.
On 1 December 2022, the matter came before Senior Judicial Registrar Malinowsky for interim hearing. Judgment was delivered on 2 December 2022, and orders were made for the child to live with the mother, spend supervised time with the father between three and five hours in length on each Tuesday and Saturday, and require the parents to communicate via a parenting application. Further, the Court ordered that the parents be retrained from making derogatory comments towards one another and physically disciplining the child, that the child’s name be placed on the Family Law Watchlist and that the father subject himself to hair follicle testing.
On 23 December 2022, Senior Judicial Registrar Malinowsky released the father’s Local Court file to the parties.
On 23 February 2023, the matter came before Judicial Registrar Bistolaridis. By consent the parties agree to discharge their existing appointments before a Court Child Expert, and to appoint a Single Joint Expert to produce a Family Report pursuant to the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia (Family Law) Rules 2021 (Cth) (“the Rules”).
On 9 June 2023, the matter came before McClelland DCJ for a compliance and readiness hearing. The matter was listed before this Court for final hearing with an estimated hearing time of five days and filing deadlines were made to facilitate such a hearing.
On 10 November 2023, the matter came before Senior Judicial Registrar Hayward. Orders were made by consent providing for the father to pay the mother $1,200 per month in spousal maintenance and for the father to deliver the mother’s diamond ring to the mother’s solicitor.
On 29 November 2023, the matter came before this Court for the first time, and the proceedings were listed for interim hearing.
On 8 April 2024, this Court made various contested and consent orders. The orders allowed the father to correspond with the child’s day care, to attend special events at the day care, for various procedural information to be exchanged between the parties and for further amendments to the filing directions of McClelland DCJ.
On 13 May 2024, this Court delivered judgment in the interim matter between the parties. By consent the parties agreed to discharge supervised contact between the father and the child, and for the father to spend unsupervised time from 8:00 am to 6:00 pm each Tuesday and Saturday with the child.
On 6 September 2024, this Court dismissed the mother’s application pursuant to s 14(1)(b) of the Regulations.
On 25 November 2024, the parents attended a conciliation conference with Judicial Registrar Ferreira and reached “an in principle final agreement regarding financial matters” (Orders 25 November 2024, notation A). It is noted that aspects of this agreement are alleged to not have occurred and fall within the scope of the issues to be determined by this Court.
On 3 February 2025, the matter came before this Court for final hearing. On 4 February 2025 the matter was adjourned for the balance of the day due to concerns regarding the interpretation and translation of the mother’s evidence. This resulted in the Court provided interpreter being discharged. On 5 February 2025, the matter returned with a different interpreter to allow for the parties to cross-examine a Single Expert on Japanese law. The balance of the hearing was, however, adjourned to 4 August 2025.
On 5 February 2025, this Court conducted an interim hearing of the father’s Application in a Proceeding filed 5 February 2025.
On 18 February 2025, this Court delivered judgment in an interim application between the parents necessitated by the adjournment of the substantive proceedings until August 2025. Contested orders were made providing the father with greater unsupervised time with the child, including overnight time. Orders by consent were made detailing an agreed changeover location and for certain information and authorities to be exchanged and signed between the parents.
On 5 August 2025, the second day of the second tranche of the final hearing in this matter, this Court made an order allowing the issue of a short service subpoena to New South Wales Police Force (“the Police”) specifically in relation to the production of a DVEC recording of the mother.
On 6 August 2025, judgment was reserved in the substantive proceeding. As the parties had not concluded their submissions, were in dispute over what material was to be read, and the short service subpoena had not yet been produced, orders providing a mechanism by which various documents and submissions were to be filed were made.
On 25 August 2025, the matter was listed before Campton J (in my absence) noting issues arising from the orders made 6 August 2025. A further order was made for the production of a “DVEC recording” from the Police and for an extension of deadlines regarding final submissions.
On 11 September 2025, the matter came before this Court noting non-compliance with the orders of Campton J. Orders were made clarifying what material is to be read in the matter, extending time for the mother to file submission in reply and for the respondent to provide a further tender bundle, as agreed between the parties, via email to Chambers upon which judgment be formally reserved once more.

EVIDENCE BEFORE THE COURT

In support of his case, the father relies upon the following material:
(1) Outline of Case Document filed 31 January 2025;

(2) His affidavit filed 29 April 2024;

(3) His affidavit filed 8 November 2024;

(4) His affidavit filed 25 January 2025;

(5) His updating affidavit filed 30 July 2025;

(6) Written submissions filed 8 September 2025 (“father’s written submissions”); and

(7) Various documents tendered during the proceedings as Exhibits A1–A22.

In support of her case, the mother relies upon the following material:
(1) Addendum Outline of Case Document filed 31 January 2025;

(2) Her two affidavits filed 13 February 2025;

(3) Her updating affidavit filed 21 July 2025;

(4) Affidavit of Dr DD (“[Dr DD]”) filed 26 April 2024;

(5) Affidavit of Ms U filed 8 May 2024;

(6) Affidavit of Mr M filed 5 May 2025;

(7) Affidavit and Report of Ms EE filed 6 July 2025;

(8) Written submissions of the mother received 8 September 2025 (“mother’s written submissions”);

(9) Written submissions in reply received 22 September 2025 (“mother’s written submissions in reply”); and

(10) Various documents tendered during the proceedings as Exhibits R1–R25.

In support of her case, the Independent Children’s Lawyer relies upon the following material:
(1) Outline of Case Document filed 2 February 2025;

(2) Single Joint Expert Report of Dr F dated 10 April 2024;

(3) Written Submissions filed 10 September 2025 (“Independent Children’s Lawyer’s written submissions”); and

Various documents tendered during the proceedings as ICL1–ICL7. Despite the volume of material relied on in this matter only the mother, father, Dr DD and Dr F were cross-examined during the hearing. It is not necessary to make overarching, credit findings in the circumstances of this matter for the reasons outlined by Kent J in Carlson & Fluvium [2012] FamCA 32 at [165]–[169].

THE PARENTING PROCEEDINGS

The father’s proposal

The father’s final Minute of Orders Sought was provided to the Court on 6 August 2025 and is contained in Exhibit A19. This proposal sets out a primary and a secondary position and is reproduced at annexure one to these reasons for judgment.
The father’s primary position is that the child is not permitted to relocate to Japan with the mother, the secondary being the propounded orders if the Court determines that the child should be permitted to relocate to Japan with the mother. A broad overview the substance of the father’s proposals are as follows:

Common Orders Across Primary and Secondary Positions

That the parents share “parental responsibility” for the child;
Should this not be ordered that the father be granted sole major long-term decision-making authority for the child;
That changeovers occur at V Street, Suburb Y or O Daycare or School if the child is attending school, or such other place as agreed between the parties in writing.

Should the Child Remain in Australia

That the mother be restrained from relocating with the child to Japan;
That the child spend time with the father during the school term in a gradually increasing regime;
That this regime commences with the child spending, for an initial six-month period, from each Tuesday from 9:30 am until 9:30 am the following Wednesday, and from each second Friday from 3:30 pm until Sunday at 3:30 pm with the father;
That this regime culminates at the end of 18 months with the child spending time with the father on a week-about basis with changeover to occur at the commencement of school, or 9:00 am (the Court presumes that the father intends this to be the commencement of school on Monday);
That the child spend time with the father during school holidays in 2026 in blocks of three nights and four days weekly;
From the commencement of “the long school holidays” in 2026 and thereafter the child is to spend week-about time with the father during school holidays (the Court presumes that the father means the Christmas or end of year holidays through his reference to the “long school holidays”);
That, subject to numerous caveats, the mother be permitted to travel to Japan with the child for the entirety of the first and third set of school holidays each year;
That from 2027 the father be able to travel to Country B with the child for up to four weeks during the “long school holidays each year”;
That the child be permitted to spend time with both parents on various special occasions;
That the non-caring parent be given a right of first refusal to care for the child in the event that the parent ordinarily with care of the child is unable to care for the child;
That the parents exchange various information between one another;
That the mother be restrained from obtaining passports or travel documents in the child’s name; and
That the parents be restrained from denigrating one another in the presence of the child.

Should the Child be Permitted to Relocate to Japan

That the mother not be permitted to relocate to Japan with the child until the child turns seven (7) years old;
That the father shall spend school term time with the child in the following manner:
For an initial six-month period, each Tuesday from 9:00 am until 9:00 am Wednesday and each second Friday from 3:00 pm until the following Sunday (No indication of cessation of time is indicated for this Sunday changeover);
For a six-month period thereafter, each Tuesday from 9:00 am until 9:00 am the following Wednesday and each second Friday from the conclusion of daycare (no specific time is provided) until 9:00 on the following Monday.
During the 2026 school holidays the father spend block time of three nights and four days with the child during each week of the “short” school holiday periods (the Court infers this to mean the school holiday periods following terms one (1), two (2) and three (3));
From the beginning of the “long” school holiday in 2026 and thereafter the father seeks week about time with the child during all school holiday time;
That, should the child elect following their relocation to Japan, that the father spend the entirety of the Japanese summer school holidays, and for two weeks as agreed during the Australian Summer holidays (including time over Christmas, if requested) with the father;
For each week the father spends in Japan following the child’s relocation that the child spends block time of five (5) nights with the father; and
That the mother ensure the child is able to videocall the father on no less than two (2) occasions each week for up to thirty (30) minutes on each occasion.
Further, and separately, the father seeks a suite of orders be made to account for circumstances in which the mother relocates, or spends time outside of the Commonwealth of Australia, without the Child. These orders do not warrant summary or reproduction.

The mother’s proposal

The mother’s Final Minute of Orders Sought was provided on 6 August 2025, marked as Exhibit R13 and is reproduced as annexure two to these reasons for judgment.
Similar to the father, she presented a dual proposal to the Court. Her primary position was that she be allowed to relocate with the child to Japan, with a secondary position of propounded orders if the Court refuses her application to relocate. A broad overview the substance of the mother’s proposals are as follows:
Regardless of which proposal is ultimately favoured by the Court, she seeks that she has sole decision-making authority for all long-term issues regarding the child, that the father be able to provide comment on the exercise of this power through a procedural feedback mechanism and that the child live with the mother.

Common Orders Across Primary and Secondary Positions

That the mother have sole decision-making authority in respect to all major long-term decisions in relation to the child;
That the child live with the mother and spend some time with the father;
That the mother retain the child’s passports;
That the child attend upon counselling with her current provider, or another similarly suitably qualified mental health practitioner during her time in Japan;
That the father shall pay for all of the child and the mother travel expenses (to Australia) while the child resides in Japan;
That the mother shall pay for all of the child’s travel expenses (to Japan) while the child resides in Australia;
That the father pay for the child’s school fees to attend Japanese International School located at Suburb W if the child is to remain in residing in Australia; and
That the mother pay for the child’s Japanese School while in Australia and the child’s English School while in Japan.

If Permitted to Relocate to Japan

That the parents do all things necessary to register the father “on the Child’s Family Registry” in Japan;
That the parents do all things, including appoint legal representatives, to register mirror or consent orders in the terms provided by this Court with the Family Court of Kyoto;
That upon arriving in Japan, amongst other procedural things, that the mother will do all things necessary to enrol the child in identified day care programs and in varying English language school programs;
That the mother facilitate videocalls between the child and the father each Tuesday and Saturday, when not otherwise spending time with the father, between 6:30 pm and 7:00 pm local time in Japan;
That the mother update the father on a monthly basis, when the child is not otherwise spending time with the father, as to the child’s general wellbeing;
That the father spend time with the child when he is in Japan during school term in the following manner:
Until June 2026, on an alternating week by week basis, in the first week from 3:30 pm on Friday until 3:30 on Sunday, and in the second week from 3:30 pm on Tuesday to 8:30 am Wednesday;
From July 2026 onwards, on an alternating week by week basis, in the first week from 3:30 pm on Friday to 3:30 pm on Sunday, and in the second week from 3:30 Tuesday until 8:30 am Thursday.
For changeover to primarily occur at the mother’s place of residence;
For the father to provide advanced notice of his intention to travel to Japan, and details of his trip therein;
That the father spend gradually increasing holiday time with the child when he is in Japan in the following pattern:
In odd years between July and August of the Japanese summer school holidays;
In even years between March and April of the spring holidays and December and January of the winter school holidays;
If the father is not in Japan during holidays, that the mother facilitate gradually increasing time between the child and the father in the following pattern;
In odd years between July and August;
In even years between December and January; and
If the father is in Japan, that the child spend time with the father on certain special occasions.

If Not Permitted to Relocate to Japan

That the child spend time with the father during the school term in the following alternating arrangement:
Until 30 June 2026, in week one from 3:30 pm on Friday to 3:30 pm on Sunday, and in week two from 3:30 pm Tuesday to 8:30 am Wednesday;
From July 2026 in week one from 3:30 Friday to 3:30 Sunday, and in week two from 3:30 pm Tuesday to 8:30 am Thursday;
That changeovers occur at the police station closest to the mother’s place of residence unless it would be more practical for it to be done at the child’s school;
That the child spend time with the parents in an unorthodox gradually increasing manner in the following pattern:
In even years with the father in term two and term four school holidays;
In odd years with the father in the term one and term three school holidays;
In even years the mother be at liberty to spend term one and term three school holidays in Japan with the child;
In odd years the mother be a liberty to spend term two and term four school holidays in Japan with the child; and
That the child spend certain special occasion time with either parent.

The Independent Children’s Lawyer

The Independent Children’s Lawyer provided a Final Minute of Order Sought on 6 August 2025. This was marked as Exhibit ICL5, and is reproduced as annexure three to these reasons for judgment. By way of broad overview, the Independent Children’s Lawyer contends that the Court should permit the mother to relocate to Japan, and that the Court should make the following orders to facilitate that:
That all previous orders be discharged;
That the mother have sole responsibility for making decisions in relation to all long-term issues relating to the child;
That the child live with the mother;
That prior to the mother relocating to Japan she do certain enumerated things to register the father on the child’s family registry in Japan and to register the orders of this Court such that they are operable and enforceable in Japan;
That the mother’s solicitors provide the father with at least 30 days notice of her intention to relocate;
That the mother be solely responsible for any expenses related to her relocation to Japan with the child;
That the mother do all things to enrol the child in a daycare and/or school program in Japan with a suitable English language program;
That the mother facilitates video calls between the child and the father each Tuesday and Saturday during times in which the child in not spending other time with the father;
That the mother provides a monthly update to the father as to the child’s progress and wellbeing;
Whenever the father in in Japan, the child spend time with the father during the school term for three (unspecified) nights per week;
That changeover occur at the mother’s place of residence unless it is more convenient to do so at the child’s school or daycare;
That the father provide a minimum notice period of fourteen day alongside other procedural details of any intention to travel to Japan;
When the father is in Japan, that the child spend time holiday time with the father in a gradually increasing regime;
If the father is not in Japan, that the mother facilitate the child’s travel to Australia during holiday time in a gradually increasing regime;
That the father pay for the costs of travel and accommodation for the mother and the child when they travel to Australia for the purpose of holiday time;
That the child spend certain special occasion time with the parents;
That the mother retain the child’s passports;
That the parents sign all document required to cause the child to attend counselling with their current mental health practitioner before relocating to Japan;
That the father pay for the child to attend a Japanese international school whilst the child remains residing in Australia;
That the mother pay for the child to attend Japanese School whilst in Australia and English School whilst residing in Japan;
That the parents communicate in writing;
That the parents provide certain enumerated authorisations; and
That the parents be subject to certain incidental restraints.

ISSUES FOR DETERMINATION

There are a number of issues in these proceedings for the Court to determine:
Whether the mother should be permitted to relocate to Japan with the child;
Whether any orders made by this Court will be registerable and/or otherwise enforceable in Japan in the event that the mother be permitted to relocate to Japan with the child;
What time the father should spend with the child;
How should parental responsibility and decision-making authority in respect of major long-term issues for the children be allocated;
Whether any family violence occurred, and if so, what impact does that have on the parenting arrangements for the child;
What, if any, financial orders ought to be made; and
What other incidental orders should be made in the best interests of the child.

THE APPLICABLE LAW

The applicable law is found in Part VII of the Act. The Family Law Amendment Act 2024 (Cth) (“the Amendment Act”) came into effect on 6 May 2024 and made substantive amendments to the previous Act which apply to these proceedings. In determining parenting matters under Part VII of the Act the Court must still regard the best interests of the child as the paramount consideration: s 60CA.
The objects and principles of Part VII are set out at s 60B:
60B Objects of Part

The objects of this Part are:
(a) to ensure that the best interests of children are met, including by ensuring their safety; and

(b) to give effect to the Convention on the Rights of the Child done at New York on 20 November 1989.

In regard to parental responsibility, the presumption of equal shared parental responsibility as created by the previous s 61DA of the Act has been abolished. Instead, s 61D(3) of the Act provides the Court with the ability to deal with the allocation of responsibility for making decisions in relation to children as follows:
61D Parenting orders and parental responsibility

...
(3) A parenting order that deals with the allocation of responsibility for making decisions about major long-term issues in relation to the child (see subsection 64B(3)) may provide for joint or sole decision-making in relation to all or specified major long-term issues.
Section 61DAA of the Act provides the Court with an understanding of what joint decision-making about major long-term issues entails:
61DAA Effect of parenting order that provides for joint decision-making about major long-term issues
(1) If a parenting order provides for joint decision-making by persons in relation to all or specified major long-term issues in relation to a child, then, except to the extent the order otherwise specifies, the order is taken to require each of the persons:
(a) to consult each other person in relation to each such decision; and

(b) to make a genuine effort to come to a joint decision.
(2) To avoid doubt, this section does not require any other person to establish, before acting on a decision about the child communicated by one of those persons, that the decision has been made jointly.
Subject to any order to the contrary, s 61DAB clarifies that if a child is spending time with a person under a parenting order, the order is not taken to require that person to consult with a person who has parental responsibility about decisions that are made in relation to the child that are not major long-term issues.
Because s 60CA and s 60B refer to the best interests of the child, the Court must consider s 60CC which specifies how the Court determines what is in a child’s best interests:
60CC How a court determines what is in a child’s best interests

Determining child's best interests
(1) Subject to subsection (4), in determining what is in the child’s best interests, the court must:
(a) consider the matters set out in subsection (2); and
(b) if the child is an Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander child—also consider the matters set out in subsection (3).
General considerations
(2) For the purposes of paragraph (1)(a), the court must consider the following matters:
(a) what arrangements would promote the safety (including safety from being subjected to, or exposed to, family violence, abuse, neglect, or other harm) of:
(i) the child; and
(ii) each person who has care of the child (whether or not a person has parental responsibility for the child);
(b) any views expressed by the child;

(c) the developmental, psychological, emotional and cultural needs of the child;

(d) the capacity of each person who has or is proposed to have parental responsibility for the child to provide for the child’s developmental, psychological, emotional and cultural needs;

(e) the benefit to the child of being able to have a relationship with the child’s parents, and other people who are significant to the child, where it is safe to do so;

(f) anything else that is relevant to the particular circumstances of the child.

(2A) In considering the matters set out in paragraph (2)(a), the court must include consideration of:
(a) any history of family violence, abuse or neglect involving the child or a person caring for the child (whether or not the person had parental responsibility for the child); and

(b) any family violence order that applies or has applied to the child or a member of the child’s family.

(Emphasis in original)
The new legislative focus is on promoting the safety of children and carers, whereas the former provisions focused on protection from harm. The legislature must have intended there to be a distinction between the former provisions, which focused on protection from harm, and the current provisions which focus on the promotion of safety, otherwise the amendments would lack utility (Melounis & Melounis (No 4) [2024] FedCFamC1F 778). The amendments require a more nuanced, proactive and future-focused approach to considering the safety of children and those who care for them. This will be guided by historical risk assessment.
As stated by Campton J in Barnabas & Phineus [2025] FedCFamC1A 215 at [17]:
The construction of Pt VII of the Family Law Act 1975 (Cth) (“the Act”) after the 2024 amendments reinforces the consideration of the safety of children or another person as a focused starting point in those considerations to be weighed in determining a parenting regime that best promotes the best interests of the children (Pierce & Pierce (No 2) [2025] FedCFamC1A 162 at [31]).

Emphasis added
Acknowledging this, the Court cautions against lapsing into simplistic binaries such as contending that promoting safety is always different from protection from harm. The reality is much more nuanced. Every case is different. Perhaps in many cases it will make no difference which approach is adopted, but in other cases the nuanced, proactive and future-focused difference is very important to the child and carer.
It should further be noted that due to the repeal of the former s 65DAA of the Act, there is no longer the statutory requirement for the Court consider equal time or substantial and significant time. Cases that refer to this section will need to be carefully considered as to whether they still apply in limited ways, if at all.
The definition of family violence is found in s 4AB of the Act, reproduced below:
4AB Definition of family violence etc.
(1) For the purposes of this Act, family violence means violent, threatening or other behaviour by a person that coerces or controls a member of the person’s family (the family member), or causes the family member to be fearful.

(2) Examples of behaviour that may constitute family violence include (but are not limited to):

(a) an assault; or

(b) a sexual assault or other sexually abusive behaviour; or

(c) stalking; or

(d) repeated derogatory taunts; or

(e) intentionally damaging or destroying property; or

(f) intentionally causing death or injury to an animal; or
(g) unreasonably denying the family member the financial autonomy that he or she would otherwise have had; or

(h) unreasonably withholding financial support needed to meet the reasonable living expenses of the family member, or his or her child, at a time when the family member is entirely or predominantly dependent on the person for financial support; or

(i) preventing the family member from making or keeping connections with his or her family, friends or culture; or

(j) unlawfully depriving the family member, or any member of the family member’s family, of his or her liberty.

(3) For the purposes of this Act, a child is exposed to family violence if the child sees or hears family violence or otherwise experiences the effects of family violence.

(4) Examples of situations that may constitute a child being exposed to family violence include (but are not limited to) the child:

(a) overhearing threats of death or personal injury by a member of the child’s family towards another member of the child’s family; or

(b) seeing or hearing an assault of a member of the child’s family by another member of the child’s family; or

(c) comforting or providing assistance to a member of the child’s family who has been assaulted by another member of the child’s family; or

(d) cleaning up a site after a member of the child’s family has intentionally damaged property of another member of the child’s family; or

(e) being present when police or ambulance officers attend an incident involving the assault of a member of the child’s family by another member of the child’s family.

The section is both remedial and protective and as such should not be read down by artificial limitations (Project Blue Sky Inc v Australian Broadcasting Authority (1998) 194 CLR 355).
Disputed allegations of family violence must be subjected to the same forensic rigour as any other contested factual issue (Edinger & Duy [2023] FedCFamC1A 194; (2023) 68 Fam LR 55). The party alleging the fact bears the burden of proving it (Wallaby Grip Ltd v QBE Insurance (Australia) Ltd (2010) 240 CLR 444 at [36]) and the standard of the burden is the balance of probabilities (s 140 of the Evidence Act 1995 (Cth)). The same point was recently made by the Full Court, though perhaps in less robust terms (Leventis & Leventis [2024] FedCFamC1A 141; (2024) FLC 94-204 at [13]–[19]).

THE SINGLE JOINT EXPERT REPORT

The primary expert evidence available to the Court is the Single Joint Expert Report of Dr F dated 10 April 2024 (“Single Expert Report”). The Single Joint Expert was cross-examined. From the reasons that follow, the Court accepts his oral and written evidence.
All references in this section, unless explicitly indicated to the contrary, should be construed as referring to the Single Expert Report.

Interview with the mother

The Court notes that the mother did not speak any English throughout the interview, and all her comments were translated by an interpreter (paragraph 6). The Single Joint Expert remarked on the mother’s approach to these Court proceedings by highlighting the oddity of the mother requiring a translator during the interview despite the fact that “when asked what language [the mother] had used throughout her relationship with [the father], [the mother] stated that they had spoken in English” (paragraph 7). This was a seemingly irrelevant observation, and no conclusion flows from it. Nothing more can be inferred from this.
The Single Joint Expert noted that “[the mother] presented as a meek and frightened woman of Japanese descent, with a profoundly anxious demeanour” (paragraph 6) and that “she displayed what was considered to be an overprotective manner with her daughter, [the child] showing obvious signs of worry about the day” (paragraph 6). The Single Joint Expert did however caution the Court against construing the mother’s affect as being indicative of any diagnosed Post Traumatic Stress Disorder (“PTSD”): “the Court is advised to be quite cautious about placing any reliance on the term PTSD as applied diagnostically to [the mother] (paragraph 11). Thus, the Court is not asked to ignore the existence of the mother’s affect, but only to refrain from inferring that such affect is symptomatic of PTSD as it is medically understood.
Regarding the mother’s approach to reporting process the Single Joint Expert remarked “... at times she showed evidence of a total lack of flexibility in her thinking, changing her responses when it became evident that they did not correspond with her previous narrative, seemingly attempting to control the outcome of the assessment” (paragraph 6).

Interview with the father

The father was described by the Single Joint Expert as “a reasonably sensible and practical man, willing to take responsibility for his actions and openly discussing the negative allegations made against him without obvious defensiveness or unnecessary denials” (paragraph 36). This impression continued: “[the father] showed a willingness to be flexible in his proposals to find a final parenting arrangement that worked for all the parties, but in particular for [the child]” (paragraph 36). Ultimately, the father was assessed by the Single Joint Expert as having “positive insight into his current circumstances and also to the impact that may have on [the child] should the circumstances surrounding her care be changed” (paragraph 77).

Observation of the child

The child was observed alongside both parents. The Single Joint Expert explained that the child, upon initial observation, appeared to “be a shy child of a stated age. Although quiet, she appeared to be at ease in [the] mother’s company, as well as with the strangers in the room” (paragraph 88). When it came time for the mother to leave, the Single Joint Expert noted that the child appeared reluctant for her to depart (paragraph 88). The child did not appear to recognise the father at first, however once comforted by the father it appeared that the child “enjoyed her father being around her and liked being physically close to him” (paragraph 89).

Determinations

The Single Joint Expert at paragraph 107 “determined” that the father’s parental capacity is positive, “and should the Court come to a similar conclusion, it is suggested that the need for ongoing supervision via a professional contact agency can be wound up”. As an ancillary recommendation, the Single Joint Expert maintained that it would be of benefit if the parents “engage in considerable parent education programs to further develop their respective parenting skills” (paragraph 107).
At paragraph 109, the Single Joint Expert expressed caution about decision making in relation to relocation noting the status of the Hague Convention in Japan, without ensuring that her proposal “is more carefully considered and placed under even greater scrutiny”. The Court notes this. The legal implications of an international recovery are matters for the Court to consider, not the Single Joint Expert.
The Single Joint Expert opined that “[the mother] has consistently shown herself to be unwilling and strongly opposed to any co-parenting agreement with [the father] since their separation...[the father] faces the very real likelihood of further Court applications in Japan in order to see and spend time with his daughter...” (paragraph 109).
Regarding the child’s attachment to the parents, the Single Joint Expert opined that “her wishes can only be gleaned by her observed attachment bond with both parents” as she was young and could not be relied upon to have a “practical understanding of with whom she lives and spends time with...” (paragraph 110). On balance, the Single Joint Expert opined that the child had “an observably positive bond with both parents”, and that this weighed in favour of “the possibility of a shared care relationship between the homes of both parents” (paragraph 110). The Court finds these tentative conclusions surprising. Attachment is based on limited observations which, somehow, lead to the possibility of shared care of a three-year-old child (at the time) with a father who (the Court will find) perpetrated family violence and showed limited insight about this. This is also contrary to the conclusion in the last sentence of paragraph 115 where the Single Joint Expert seems to indicate that shared care is contraindicated. In cross-examination the Single Joint Expert clarified that he meant that the child had an emotional attachment to the father, but he was unable to say that it was a secure attachment. He also accepted that if the Court found that family violence occurred, safety must be maximised as such violence shapes a child’s development.
The Single Joint Expert expressed concern about the mother’s willingness to “consult with [the father] for any important decisions regarding [the child’s] care” and that as a result “she would need therapeutic support to assist her genuine compliance with Orders” should the Court determine that a shared care arrangement is in the child’s best interest (paragraph 112). In cross-examination he agreed that it was insightful of the mother to acknowledge that she needed therapy, and that it was good that she was aware of her own frailties and vulnerabilities.
Should the Court allocate to the mother decision making for all major long-term decisions pertaining to the child, the Single Joint Expert warned “it would be probable that [the father] would not be consulted for any important decisions for [the child’s] upbringing, and when noting [the mother’s] poor command of the English language, it may well be the most viable option to provide sole parental responsibility to [the father]” (paragraph 113).
In relation to the mother’s proposal the Single Joint Expert stated at paragraph 114, “should [the child] be allowed to relocate to Japan, at the very best she will experience a diminishment, if not total suspension of her relationship with [the father], which is not considered to be a positive outcome for [the child’s] long-term development, and at worst she will lose all contact with [the father]”. The Single Joint Expert reinforced this by stating “the role of both parents in [the child’s] life is considered to be of great importance and, as such, should be preserved” (paragraph 114). If this language was intended to reflect the now redundant presumption of equal shared parental responsibility, it is problematic. As merely a general proposition, however, the Court agrees. In any event in cross-examination, the Single Joint Expert conceded that relocation with contact four times annually would maintain the father’s connection to the child, but that the relationship would be negatively impacted by the reduction in time and physical connection.
The Single Joint Expert stated, above all, that “[the mother] was found to be a loving mother, who’s role in [the child’s] life is imperative and should not be compromised due to having to co-parent with [the father]” (paragraph 115). The Single Joint Expert “strongly recommended” that the mother “engage in psychological therapy, outside of a Victim Services umbrella” and that “she would also benefit from undertaking English classes” (paragraph 115).

Family Violence

The Single Joint Expert was cautious when discussing family violence in this matter. At paragraph 104, the Single Joint Expert opined that:
... it was noted that [the father]and [the mother] had starkly contrasting narratives as to the nature of their relationship and the violence which [the father] was alleged to have perpetrated upon [the mother] and [the child]. [The mother’s] documentation as supplied provided support to her experience of violence. It is noted however, that the documents are based on [the mother’s] self-report and post-date the time of the party’s separation, and evidence only reiteration of her own narrative.
The highest the Single Joint Expert was prepared to take his analysis can be found at paragraph 105, “It is apparent that [the father] and [the mother] have had a challenging relationship history with [the mother] reporting multiple allegations of domestic violence throughout their union.”.
When assessing the impact of any alleged family violence on the child, it was said, in relation to the mother at paragraph 128:
Should the Court find that [the child] has been exposed to family violence, it can be stated that [the mother] has considerable insight into and understanding of the impact of exposing her daughter to the alleged family violence. She has shown her ability to protect [the child] from further exposure by removing her from the home and seeking the protection of them both through the ADVO. She will have also protected [the child] from any potential risks by ensuring that [the father] is accountable to the protection provided by the ADVO and requesting the requirement that [the child] be supervised during the time she spends with her father.
In relation to the father, it was suggested at paragraph 129:
When considering [the father], he has also shown that he has insight and understanding of the impact of exposing a child to family violence. He expressed his distress about the argument that ensued between himself and [the mother] on the day of separation and has subsequently followed the parenting agreements made, including extensive supervision of his time with his daughter. He has also completed multiple parenting courses in order to gain further understanding and skills in parenting following separation.
In cross-examination the Single Joint Expert explained that he found the mother’s account of violence to be genuine and sincere in the context of his professional experience undertaking thousands of interviews with persons who had experienced trauma in their lives. He was conscious of deception and exaggeration. He was aware that the mother’s therapy included Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing, for trauma, which aimed to helped her manage her experience and re-experience of trauma. As it turns out, and the Court finds, that the trauma she is receiving therapy for, was most likely caused by the father’s violence towards her.
In cross-examination, the Single Joint Expert conceded that if the Court found the father had perpetrated family violence, then father had deceived him about this. In these circumstances, the mother’s persistence in facilitating the child’s relationship with her father, despite the family violence, reflected well on her commitment to facilitating the relationship, which in itself was a positive indicator if relocation were allowed. Moreover, as a survivor of the father’s violence, the Single Joint Expert accepted that the mother would feel more settled in her home country, and her greater sense of personal security would enhance her self-confidence and parenting. He explained that for the mother to engage with someone who has hurt her is very much to her credit. Indeed, he described it as “courageous”. The Single Joint Expert further accepted that the mother experienced isolation in Australia where her existing contacts and relationships are shallow. If her experience of isolation continued, it could compromise the quality of her care.

Recommendations

Balancing all factors together, the Single Joint Expert’s recommendation to the Court in this matter was:
In sum, it is my opinion that the Court could weigh more favourably the option of [the child] continuing to reside Australia so as to preserve [the child’s] current care arrangements. That said, [the child] would benefit from spending substantial and significant time with her father as well as her mother, ultimately progressing to the point of a 50/50 shared care arrangement with [the mother] and [the father]. Such an arrangement could begin by removing the requirement for supervision for [the father’s] time with his daughter. Time between them could immediately increase over a series steps [sic] to include an overnight stay each fortnight, with [the child] seeing her father from 9am Saturday to 4pm Sunday each alternate weekend. This time could also continue to include the Tuesday day from 9-5pm in the alternate week.
Time should incrementally increase to include one further overnight each six-month period to allow [the child] to adjust to the changes. Ultimately coming to a 50/50 shared care arrangement. Both parties should be informed that this arrangement should be conditional on remaining mindful of the geographical location of their living arrangements, ensuring that they are able to reasonably and reliably facilitate [the child’s] travel between the houses and school in the future. Though noting concerns expressed above, the Court may need to give consideration of directing that parents do not move beyond a certain geographic radius of [the child’s] agreed pre-school and/or school. Shared parental responsibility should be confirmed, with a nominated GP or Paediatrician agreed upon by both parties, should also be directed to exercise a casting vote in the case of parental disagreement about proposed need for treatment, as this is considered to be the most viable outcome for this complex matter, which will be beneficial to all parties, but in particular for [the child] throughout her development.
The evidence of the Single Joint Expert in the Single Expert Report, and in cross-examination, was appropriately different. Any scepticism about the father’s family violence in the Single Expert Report quite quickly dissipated when he confronted the possibility that the Court would find in the mother’s favour about the violence. The Court will find that the father did perpetrate serious physical family violence on the mother in the presence of the child. The concessions made by the Single Joint Expert in cross-examination cast the recommendations set out above in a completely different light.

Family Violence

The mother seeks that the Court make findings of fact in respect of family violence that may be broadly grouped into two separate categories. The first being findings in respect of the incidents that occurred on 24 July 2021 which precipitated the end of the parent’s relationship and incentivised the mother to attempt to board a flight to Japan with the child shortly thereafter. The second being three separate incidents that involve the father seeing or coming into contact with the mother in public spaces whilst being subject to an active ADVO that prohibited such intentional conduct. The purpose of the findings in respect of the second category of incidents was to advance a contended case of repeated “stalking” conduct by the father towards the mother.
The Court pauses to question, given the proposals advanced by the parents, what role any findings sought in respect of family violence may play in the end outcome of this matter? This was, subtly, acknowledged by the mother’s counsel at the outset of the second August 2025 tranche of these proceedings by her comment to the effect that any risk pled by the mother had “reducing relevance” in this matter. Regardless, the Court shall evaluate what it will call the “mid-2021 incident” and “Stalking” incidents as there may be some slight probative value to such course. Notwithstanding this, the violence allegations need to be treated seriously given the importance of this factor in determining how the safety of the children can be promoted. It is the experience of this Court that even single incidents of family violence can cast a shadow on later events, and the experience of the victim.

The 24July 2021 incident

The mother seeks factual findings in respect of events that occurred on 24 July 2021 (mother’s written submissions, paragraph 18). It is not disputed that, as a direct result of the 24 July 2021 incident, the father was subject to an ADVO for the mother’s protection that covered the period from late 2022 until late 2024. Such ADVO was ordered despite that father not being found guilty of the three charges brought against him (father’s 29 April affidavit, paragraph 113). Axiomatically, the father was found not guilty of the conduct the mother asserted in the criminal trial as assessed to the standard of “beyond a reasonable doubt”. Being a civil Court, this Court may take note of the not guilty verdict issued by the Local Court against the father but must separately determine whether the father perpetrated family violence according to s 4AB of the Act “on the balance of probabilities”.
The mothers her contentions in respect of the 24 July 2021 incident and its aftermath warrant setting out. She asserted that the father physically assaulted her by some combination of pushes, shoves, stomps and non-fatal strangulation. She also contended that following the physical acts of violence, that the father paced around the parents’ apartment whilst yelling and threatening her. Such conduct allegedly occurred in circumstances that would have exposed the parent’s infant child, at the time of the incident, to the father’s conduct.
The father vehemently denies committing any act of family violence against the mother. Indeed, according to the father’s affidavit filed 29 April 2024, he seemingly asserts he was the victim of family violence during the 21 July 2024 incident. At paragraph 87 of the same the father asserts:
[The mother] got up a short while later and we then proceeded to prepare breakfast for [the child] and feed her in the kitchen. I gave [the mother] some space to calm down as she was still very angry that I had given [the child] the dummy. [The mother] then began to argue saying words to the effect of “what’s wrong with you, you fucken [...]”. [The mother] continued with the verbal abuse towards me and I said to [the mother] words to the effect of “I can see why your ex-boyfriend cheated on you”. All of a sudden [the mother] then came around from the kitchen towards me where I was standing in the lounge area and began hitting and pushing me. I put my arms out to put space between the two of us asking her to please stop
Both parents were cross-examined on their evidence around the 21 July 2021 incident. The father not only denied that he had committed any act against the mother as asserted but actively suggested on multiple occasions that the mother’s account was fabricated. The mother alleged that the father pushed her such that her chest was up against the wall resulting in her being unable to breathe, punched her, that the mother had hit her head against the wall and that he stood on both her legs, including standing on the right leg hard enough to cause bruising. Although more unclear it is tentatively asserted by the mother that the child was initially in her arms when the father assaulted her, and then the child was placed down, then in the immediate aftermath, the father grabbed the child in a forceful manner whilst continuing to yell at the mother.
In the circumstances the Court is faced with the difficult task of verifying the veracity of two diametrically opposed versions of the 21 July 2024 incident, where both accounts are given on oath.

Oral evidence

A witness giving oral testimony must tell the truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth (Kuhl v Zurich Financial Services Australia Ltd [2011] HCA 11; (2011) 243 CLR 361). To make a finding of fact the Court “must feel an actual persuasion” as to its existence (Briginshaw v Briginshaw [1938] HCA 34; (1938) 60 CLR 336 at 361). In reaching a state of actual persuasion, it is necessary for the Court to assess the combined weight of all evidence, including circumstantial evidence, as a unified whole (Wei & Xia [2024] FedCFamC1A 65; (2024) FLC 94-186 at [163]).
As adverted to above, broad credit findings are not desirable in this matter. There is ample documentary evidence upon which to all found most necessary factual findings. As stated by Black J in Re Kit Digital Australia Pty Ltd (in liq) [2014] NSWSC 1547:
[7] ... I summarised the relevant principles in Re Colorado Products Pty Ltd (in prov liq) [2014] NSWSC 789 at [10], where I noted that the credibility of a witness and his or her veracity may be tested by reference to the objective facts proved independently of the testimony given, in particular by reference to the documents in the case, by paying particular regard to the witness's motives and the overall probabilities: Armagas Ltd v Mundogas SA [1861] LRSC 1; [1985] 1 Ll R 1 at 57; Camden v McKenzie [2007] QCA 136; [2008] 1 Qd R 39 at [34]; Craig v Silverbrook [2013] NSWSC 1687 at [141]; State of New South Wales v Hunt [2014] NSWCA 47 at [56].
This Court does, however, draw a distinction between general evidence as to the parents’ abilities, competency and dynamics and evidence relating to findings that are sought to be made about acts of family violence that are alleged to have occurred on 20 July 2021. The latter are inherently more serious in nature.
The Court commented to counsel in open Court about the mother’s demeanour in the witness box during the course of giving evidence about the 24 July 2021 incident. The witness was facing away from the bar table, and it would have been inherently unfair to rely on any observations about demeanour that were not reasonably within the view of the parties. The Court’s commentary is specifically adverted to in the Independent Children’s Lawyer’s written submissions at page four:
a. Eyes straight ahead seemingly at nothing

b. Clutching near throat

c. Blank look on her face

d. It appeared she was struggling for breath,
In cross-examination the Single Joint Expert was asked to comment on the mother’s presentation, as described above, from a clinical perspective. He described it as a truthful account of trauma, indeed a re-experience of a traumatic event, and likely to be a re-living of a previous experience, or a fragment thereof.
The Court’s observations, reinforced in part by those of the Single Joint Expert, create an impression of truth to the mother’s account. The Independent Children’s Lawyer seemingly accords with this as she notes in her written submissions that:
It is open to the Court to find that the father perpetrated physical and verbal abuse against the mother on 24 July 2021 in the presence of [X] who was [an infant]. (exhibit R10)
This Court is not bound by a criminal Court’s decision nor its standard of beyond reasonable doubt.
[Ms Jugovac] has had therapy including EMDR therapy to deal with symptoms of PTSD arising from her experiences in the relationship.
...
[the Single Joint Expert] was asked about this and among other things he said it was likely consistent with memories of physical abuse and an attempt to reground herself in the context of undergoing EMDR. He noted that it was heightened physiological behaviour in the mother “as if it was happening in this moment”...
In response to the Court recording its observations of the mother, the father attempted to obtain contemporaneous video evidence of a statement the mother gave to the police about the July 2021 incident:
The Father has been vigorously attempting to obtain a DVEC video of the Mother recounting the same event in July of 2021 which he states shows her reacting very differently. If that evidence becomes available and is of assistance to the Father, it is likely an application to adduce further evidence will be filed.

(father’s written submissions, pages 2 –3)
The Court notes that Court record shows that a short service subpoena has been returned as with a copy of the DVEC sought. The Court has not viewed the DVEC in question as there was no application for leave to tender it. Given the availability of the material and the father’s foreshadowed application to adduce the material only if it “is of assistance to the father”, the Court infers that the material provided was not of assistance to the father’s case.
In these circumstances the Court relies on its observations of the mother as she gave evidence about this incident and finds this to be compelling evidence of the truth of the mother’s evidence and chooses to rely on its initial impressions expressed to the parties during the course of the hearing.

Documentary evidence

Where possible, objective evidence and third-party records of events occurring around the July 2024 Incident should also be examined. The Court finds the mother’s written submissions on this topic helpful in identifying material germane for consideration:
The Court should find that on 24 July 2021 the father assaulted the mother in the presence of the child. Photographic evidence, contemporaneous witness statement, hospital records, and the mother’s immediate flight corroborate her account. A final AVO was made in August 2021 and extended in 2022 after breach.
...

20. This history explains the mother’s departure to Japan...
In due fairness to the father, he addresses other elements from objective records that the Court is open to consider at page 2 of his written submissions:
The Father’s case is that there was an argument in the kitchen of the parent’s home at breakfast time which included raised voices and nasty words being said but nothing more. He then left the home to cool off before returning to the apartment and finding the Mother and Child gone.

The Mother’s case is that the argument resulted in heir being pushed, chocked [sic] and kicked by the Father with the Child also suffering bruising. A single report to a Helpline was made by the Mother about an incident in which there was ‘pushing’ occurred prior to the Mother attempting to flee Australia with the Child. By the time the Mother had made reports to Police and was being examined in hospital, Exhibits A8 show that the allegations had extended to choking. By the time she was interviewed by the CIR writer 12 months later, the allegations now extended to hitting (Exhibit A9).
The photographic evidence referred to by the mother is in evidence as Exhibit R5. The photographs claim to depict the aftermath of the 24 July 2024 incident on the physical welfare of the mother and the child. As the Court understands, there is no dispute that the photographs presented are the most contemporaneous pictorial record of the mother and child’s state to the 24 July 2024 incident.
The photographs demonstrate a clear dark patch on the mother’s mid chest, a red mark in the centre of the dark patch, red marks on the upper third of the mother’s only visible arm and a small dark patch near the centre of the mother’s shoulder. The dark patches could well be already visible bruising, whilst the red marks could be friction and or scrape marks.
On the mother’s account the father allegedly bruised the child after forcefully grabbing and/or holding the child immediately after the mother was assaulted. The following two pictures contained in Exhibit R5 purport to show the resulting bruises arising for the forceful grabbing. The first picture shows some discolouration on the child’s lower back, and perhaps some darkness around the ribcage. The second photograph appears to show discolouration on the rear side of the child’s upper back and under the rib cage.
The Court finds that the mother had been assaulted by the father as she contends save as qualified below. On balance the photographs demonstrate discolouration and redness consistent with bruising and scrapes that were occasioned during the assault. The Court is not satisfied that the images tendered of the child clearly show any physical trauma, and if the Court is wrong in this regard, it is not satisfied that such bruising must have been caused because of the 24 July 2024 incident.
The Court was also taken to Exhibit R10 in support of the mother’s account being a statement by Ms Z a senior case worker for the New South Wales domestic violence telephone line. The account provided by Ms Z seems to largely accord with the mother’s recount, especially when one allows the for any natural inconsistencies that may arise from an alleged victim recounting events of an assault that occurred so recently at the time of the call.
The Court was also taken to Exhibit R7 by the mother’s counsel being records from the CC Hospital detailing the mother’s attendance at the hospital on 26 July 2024. Interestingly, the notes were produced and dated “Wednesday 27 October 2021”, sometime after the mother attended upon the hospital. To some degree, this mitigates the weight the Court can place on this document. The statements contained within Exhibit R7 are more detailed yet still consistent with the mother’s recount of the 24 July 2021 incident.
Finally, the mother contends that her attempted flight to Japan with the child heightens the likelihood of her story. Presumably this is based on the premise that a frightened mother subject to recent violence would seek to flee to her home country for respite. It is a reasonable inference to draw, and the Court does so, especially in the absence of any challenge to the contrary.
To the extent that the father in his written submissions suggested that inconsistencies in the varying accounts the mother provided of the 24 July 2021 incident to different professionals should weigh against the veracity of her account, this is rejected. All accounts demonstrate the same overarching pattern, even if they vary in respect of level of detail or in other history provided. Judicial experience indicates that victims of family violence may struggle to recount an accurate chronological history of events months or even years after a traumatic event. Respectfully, to suggest that inconsistencies in the mother account provided within the week of the event are dispositive ignores the fact that the victim may still be, herself, gradually processing the event.
On the balance of the evidence before the Court, the mother’s account of the 24 July 2021 incident is more likely than the fathers. The Court is comfortably persuaded that the father perpetrated physical family violence against the mother on this occasion, and that the child was exposed to such family violence. In cross-examination the father denied that he had difficulty controlling his temper. The facts suggest to the contrary, and his denial indicates lack of insight about his behaviour and its impact on the mother and child.
The Court notes the submission made by the father at page 3 of his written submissions:
Even if the Court were to find that this incident of family violence occurred, it does not follow that a finding that the Child is presently at unacceptable risk from the Father would follow. That would be contrary to the conduct of these parents and the evidence which has resulted, that [the child] is well supported and safe with her Father and that the Mother no longer believes that she is at risk from the Father.
It is true that the mother’s case does not explicitly contend that the child is at unacceptable risk of family violence, should she spend time with the father. Nonetheless the finding of family violence remains an important consideration in determining the parenting orders that promote her safety and assessing the best interests of the child. The finding of family violence makes the mother’s diagnosis of PTSD more plausible. This potentially undermines her parenting and provides a reasonable hypothesis for her attitude towards the child which could be described as overly protective and possibly hypervigilant. Thus, the finding of family violence provides a lens to understand her subsequent behaviour.

Stalking

It was also alluded throughout cross-examination that findings of fact may have been sought in relation to conduct which the mother asserts amounted to “stalking” by the father. This was not pressed by any party in their written submissions. To the extent that a finding may be sought, and may be relevant, the Court finds that the evidence does not indicate that any form of violent or stalking behaviour occurred.

Property settlement

Prior to discussing, in depth, the various parenting proposals of the parents it is unfortunately necessary to discuss disquiet that has arisen between the parents regarding property matters. The mother asserts at paragraph 27 of her affidavit dated 21 July 2025 that the father has:
... compounded my financial hardship by failing to pay the $30,000 part matrimonial property settlement on the instalment dates for $10,000 in February, March and April 2025. The Father only paid the first instalment in December 2024.
The father admitted during cross-examination that he had not paid the mother $30,000 of a $40,000 agreed property settlement payment. He further admitted that he was in breach of a “Court order” for not paying these funds. His explanation for this default was somewhat difficult to understand but circulated around an inability to refinance or sell a property owned by the parents. The Court is critical of the father for not complying with terms of an agreement he seemingly consented to. This non-payment has likely materially added to the financial struggles experienced by the mother. Impecuniosity is a factor the mother contends ought to weigh in her favour for any international relocation pressed, a matter resisted by the father. The father’s ambivalence about complying with orders of this Court reflects poorly on his attitudes as a parent.

ENFORCEABILITY OF ORDERS IN JAPAN

It is necessary to establish at the outset whether, as the mother contends, it is legally possible for orders made by this Court, to be registered, mirrored or otherwise enforced in Japan.
It is uncontroversial as between the parents that orders of foreign family law Courts can be registered in Japan. The primary dispute between the parents as to the effect of Dr DD’s evidence is the requirement of mirror orders alongside or separate to registration, and the potential for enforcement of any such recognised or mirrored orders in Japan. The Court must also determine whether it is comfortably satisfied that the parties can, and will do, all procedural steps required to register, mirror, and/or enforce the orders of this Court in Japan.

Mechanism for recognition

The affidavit of Dr DD filed 26 April 2024 (“affidavit of [Dr DD]”) is the primary source of evidence about the interrelation between Japanese domestic law and Australian family law. The mother tendered, without objection, updated questions and responses from Dr DD regarding new domestic Japanese legislation that was implemented following the filing of Dr DD’s affidavit that may impact on the dispute between the parents. These updating questions are Exhibit R1 on the Court record.
Dr DD’s affidavit, at page eight, informs that Court that Japan has ratified the Hague Convention, but not the Hague Convention on Jurisdiction, Applicable Law, Recognition, Enforcement and Co-operation in respect of Parental Responsibility and Measures for the Protection of Children 1996 (“the 1996 Hague Convention”). The 1996 Hague Convention provides for a uniform international mechanism that allows recognition and enforcement of foreign family law orders from one jurisdiction to another. Japan’s lack of ratification of the 1996 Hague Convention is the source of the enforceability issues that plague this case.
Despite this, Dr DD identified, at pages 11 and 12 of her affidavit, via reference to Article 118 of the Code of Civil Procedure (“Article 118”), that the domestic Japanese legal system has recognition mechanisms that may be applicable to the parties. Article 118 provides:
A final and binding judgment rendered by a foreign court is valid only if it meets all of the following requirements:

(i) the jurisdiction of the foreign court is recognized pursuant to laws and regulations, conventions, or treaties;

(ii) the defeated defendant has been served (excluding service by publication or any other service similar thereto) with the requisite summons or order for the commencement of litigation, or has appeared without being so served;

(iii) the content of the judgment and the litigation proceedings are not contrary to public policy in Japan;

(iv) a guarantee of reciprocity is in place.
Dr DD expands on the four subpoints within Article 118 in Exhibit R1 stating foreign family Court orders will be recognised in Japan:
As long [sic] the following criteria are met:
That the Foreign Court has jurisdiction to make those Orders
That the [sic] due process was followed
That it does not go against public or moral interest in Japan, such as Orders based on polygamy, slavery, same sex marriage, surrogate mothers or child labour.
That there is no specific legislation in that foreign country barring the recognition of Court Orders from Japan
Neither party has lead evidence, nor is the Court aware of any hurdles that would prevent Article 118 from giving effect to orders of this Court. The Court notes that other decisions of this Court have recognised the existence and potential beneficial effect of Article 118 as a recognition mechanism (Fujiwara & Suzukaze (No 2) [2022] FedCFamC1F 357).
Whilst Article 118 provides for recognition the father in particular was interested in enforcement of any orders made by this Court. In response to a question from the parents asking if Japan had a system akin to “Mirror Orders or Consent Orders” Dr DD explained:
Although it may not strictly be called a mirror order there is a system called Execution Judgment...Article 24 of the Civil Execution Act allows for a Japanese district court (or family court for cases pertaining to domestic relation) seek an execution judgment with respect to a judgment of a foreign court (amended in 2019).

In the procedure of Execution Judgment, a Japanese court examine only on the requirements of Article 118 of Code of Civil Procedure, and not reexamine the foreign judgment itself.

Since it is time-consuming and costly to obtain an execution judgment through litigation based on the strict rule of Article 24 of Civil Execution Act, the practical approach for the family affair is often obtain a "Ruling in lieu of Conciliation which has same legal contents as foreign judgment, based Article 284 of Domestic Relations Case Procedure Act, in order to give the foreign judgment legal force in Japan. This is system similar to the so-called Consent Order, the family court issues a legally enforceable ruling on the premise in the consent of the parties.

(Affidavit of Dr DD, pages 12 and 13).
Dr DD’s affidavit at pages 13–15 explain the mirror orders procedure and effect.

Contentions around enforcement

At page two of Exhibit R1, Dr DD clarifies that foreign family court orders are enforceable in Japan “as long as an execution judgment is applied for and granted by the Family Court in Japan... A Foreign Family Court Order does not need to be registered in Japan to be enforceable”.
The main substance of the disagreement between the parties’ centres around the mechanism best suited for the enforceability needs of the parents. The mother at page five of her written submissions, contends that there is no need for the parents to do anything further than ensure the orders of this Court comply with Article 118:
27. The [local] Family Court (2021) enforced a Singapore order despite claims of adaptation and welfare, demonstrating Japanese courts’ commitment to enforcement.

28. Mirror orders are not required. Imposing them risks giving the father power to delay relocation by withholding documents. If the Court considers mirror orders appropriate, strict timelines should be imposed.
The Court has read the judgment referred to by Dr DD, as it was tendered at Exhibit R11. Regrettably, it fails to shine much light on the process the Court would undertake in the present matter, especially if the Court was minded to require any sort of mirror order.
Although not expressed clearly, the father’s contention at page four of his written submissions is almost the precise opposite of the contention advanced in the mother’s written submissions:
This is a question for expert evidence and the evidence of [Dr DD]. It is submitted on behalf of the Father that the expert evidence on this point is that Consent Orders can be made in Japan which are effectively identical to parenting orders made in Australia

The expert gave evidence at Transcript Page 14 that:

Consent orders can be changed, or the enforcement of those orders can be not recognised. Those two scenarios – I can contemplate those two scenarios where the consent orders are changed or else the enforcement is not recognised by or not followed through by the courts because consent orders are in place for many years and the courts recognise that the situation of the child and the families can change a lot. So consent orders do change.

This Court has vast experience in dealing with applications to vary final orders following fresh allegations of family violence. The Father submits that the Mother has conduct throughout these proceedings are not offset by events subsequent to February 2025.
The Court infers that the father contends that this Court ought not to be satisfied by the mother’s contention that mere consent orders provide a stringent enough enforcement mechanism by which to ensure that any orders made by this Court remain unchallenged, or unchanged in Japan.
The only other hurdle, or relevant factor to consider was raised by the mother in her 21 July 2025 affidavit in pages seven and eight under the heading “Parental Recognition”:
The Father has failed to provide to my solicitor, the required documents to register paternity in Japan.
48. It has now been over seven (7) months.

49. The Father has failed to provide the following documents:
A copy of his British passport which has been notarized by a member of the British Consulate in Sydney.
A valid passport from [Country B]. This would entail the Father attending the Embassy of [Country B] in Canberra.
A copy of his birth certificate from [Country C]. The Father previously advised that one of his family members could easily travel to [Country C] to obtain a copy of his birth certificate.

...
It is not possible to file Consent Orders in the [a local] Family Court without the Father first accepting paternity for [the child].
It is not possible for me to unilaterally declare someone the Father of [the child] so I cannot complete the process for him.

...
I do not believe it is fair that in the event that my relocation application is successful, that relocation is based on the Father’s paternity being registered in Japan considering he has had 7 months to comply with my solicitor’s requests for the documents necessary to register his name on [the child’s] birth registry in Japan.
The father tendered Exhibit A17 on this point. The document adduced appears to be correspondence between him and a staff member of the Country C consulate in Australia. The email exchange shows the father repeatedly checking in about whether any progress has been made about sourcing “a copy of my birth certificate that includes both of my parents names”. The last recorded email was sent by the father on 30 June 2025. The Court has no further evidence from the father about whether he has obtained the documents necessary for registration of his paternity in Japan.
On this basis, the Court cannot make findings as to whether the father has deliberately frustrated the mother’s attempt to register his paternity of the child in the local Family Court, or whether the father is the unfortunate recipient of bureaucratic delay. Regardless, it is undoubtedly a practical constraint which may impact how the Court fashions any orders it makes. Having regard to the totality of the evidence including that of Dr DD, the Court is satisfied that any orders it makes will be recognised in Japan but that the mirror order procedure describe by Dr DD functions as a realistic prerequisite to such orders being enforceable.
It does not follow, however, that the mirror orders procedure is a precondition to any relocation. There is no evidence suggesting that the mother would not comply with orders of this Court, especially orders that are in substance proposed by her. This is not a mother who has failed to facilitate and encourage the child’s relationship with the father. Indeed, quite the opposite is true in that she persisted with facilitating the relationship despite being a victim of the father’s violence. Once the Court has concluded that it is in the best interests of the child for her mother to be permitted to relocate the child back to her home in Japan, there is no reason to defer this whilst the mirror orders procedure takes place. At page 12 of her affidavit, Dr DD indicates that the process will take months, not weeks. The Court is confident that the mother will comply with orders compelling her to participate in this process. The Court does have some concerns that the father would delay the process, even if it is not in relation to having his name placed on the child’s birth certificate.

INTERNATIONAL RELOCATION

Having now identified that orders made by this Court be registered in Japan and can be rendered enforceable in Japan in some capacity, consideration must turn to the substantive merits of the mother’s international relocation case.

Principles

The parenting principles in Part VII of the Act apply with equal force to applications for the international relocation of a child, just as they do in other parenting applications. Indeed, in Zahawi & Rayne [2016] FamCAFC 90 at [48] the Full Court stated that:
“Relocation cases” are no different from other applications for parenting orders in that respect. Like all applications for parenting orders, an application to have the children live with a parent significantly geographically remote from the other parent is to be determined by the children’s best interests. However, the issues in a “relocation case” are, by reason of the proposed geographical separation of parents from their children, often significantly more acute and all the more so in cases of proposed international relocation. And, of course, that same factor will usually render more acute the burden or burdens to be borne by one parent or the other, including restrictions on their freedoms.
The children’s best interests are the paramount consideration when weighing up the parties’ competing proposals; s 60CA of the Act. That said, the parents’ legitimate desires and interests are not ignored, rather, where those interests conflict with the children’s best interests, the child’s best interests prevail (AMS v AIF (1999) 199 CLR 160 at [207]–[208]). Similarly, whilst a parent enjoys the right of freedom of movement to live wherever they choose, that right must defer to the paramount consideration, being what is in the child’s best interests (U v U [2002] HCA 36; (2002) 211 CLR 238 at [89]).

Preliminary findings

Any discretionary evaluative decision regarding international relocation must be based on certain findings of fact that elucidate that parents’ and child’s current circumstances, and some speculative regard as to future counterfactual realities.

The child’s schooling

By all accounts, the child appears to be well settled at school. Exhibits A3 and A4 go towards this fact. Exhibit A3 is a report on the child’s overall development dated 30 May 2025 from the child’s kindergarten. Nothing of significant concern is identified, despite the comprehensive nature of the evaluation. Exhibit A4 is a prose form “Assessment of Learning Summary” dated 30 May 2025 also by the child’s kindergarten. The Court agrees with the father’s assertion at page one of his written submissions that “the Child’s recent school report seems to indicate that the girl is thriving”.
The mother gives evidence that the child has attended a Japanese School. There do not appear to be any issues regarding the child’s education of socialisation arising from this. There is no reason to doubt, given the child’s bilingual capacity and cross-cultural ties, that attendance upon a cultural school would be beneficial. On the evidence before the Court, the child’s schooling in Australia appears to be settled and beneficial.
Should the child remain in Australia both parties agree that it would be best for her to attend the Japanese International School in Suburb W. The Court has no reason to doubt that this choice would serve the child’s cultural and educational development well. Should the mother be permitted to relocate she consents to orders that would involve the child in “[T Daycare] or similar day care with an English language program” and upon the commencement of schooling, “[S School] or similar after school English Language program”. The Court, again, has no reason to doubt that this choice would serve the child’s cultural and educational development well.
The child’s schooling does not weigh in favour of any particular proposal.

The child’s ties to Australia

The child was an infant when she first arrived in Australia with the mother. She was granted permanent residency on 13 January 2022 (father’s 25 January 2025 affidavit, paragraph 3). The child speaks both Japanese and English. Her father obtained permanent residency in Australia in 2019 and deposed that it is his “intention to continue living in Australia indefinitely” (father’s 25 January 2025 affidavit, paragraph 4). Further, the child attends school in Australia and according to Exhibit A4 has an expanding circle of friends in Australia. It thus clear that the child has been living in Australia for the majority of her life, will be able to remain living in Australia with one or both parents for as long as required, and it likely to always have a connection to Australia by way of her father who does not intend to relocate and is committed to a relationship with the child.
The Court finds that the child has a strong connection to Australia, despite not being born in Australia to two non-Australian citizen parents. This weighs in favour of the child remaining in the Commonwealth of Australia.

The child’s ties to Japan

Weight must be given to the fact that this Court determined that, as of 27 July 2021, the child was habitually a resident of Japan for the purposes of the Hague Proceedings. Whilst this is not determinative of any application under the Act, it demonstrates a clear and long-lasting connection between the child and Japan.
Aside from this, the Court does not doubt that the mother has ensured that the child maintained strong links to Japan and Japanese culture by keeping in contact with her Japanese family, sending her to a Japanese day care, and speaking Japanese at home. Indeed, the father in his oral evidence before this Court admitted to learning limited Japanese, and to reading the child’s favourite Japanese book to connect with the child whilst it is in his care (father’s 29 April 2024 affidavit, paragraphs 51 and 54). All of this speaks to strong and lasting ties between the child and Japan, despite the child having not resided in the nation in over four years.
The Court finds that the child has strong ties to Japan through the mother and her family. This weighs in favour of international relocation.

The child’s ties to the maternal and paternal families

There is no reason to doubt that the child has strong ties to the maternal and paternal families, although the nature of the connection the child shares with either side differs.
In the father’s 29 April 2024 affidavit at paragraph 165, the father provides evidence that the paternal grandparents have spent relatively prolonged time with the child in 2022, 2023 and 2024. This time however is intermittent as the paternal grandparents reside overseas. Further, it is unclear if the paternal grandparents have spent any significant time with the child since the last three month visit in 2024. Notwithstanding this, it is not subject to dispute that the child has fond feelings towards the paternal grandparents.
In the mother’s written submissions at paragraph 12 seek to cast doubt on whether the Court can rely on the father’s evidence regarding support from, and connection to, his family:
By contrast, no affidavits of support have been provided by the father’s family. His extended family remains in [Country B]; their attitudes toward [the child] and their living circumstances including where [the child] will stay if travelling to [Country B] are unknown.
The Court accepts that the father has not filed supporting material from his extended family. This does not mean that they do not care for the father or the child, nor does it mean that they would have adverse opinions on the mother, nor would they fail to support the child if it was allowed to travel to Country B.
In furtherance of her own case, at the same paragraph of her written submissions, the mother suggests that she “has strong support networks in Japan, including her parents and siblings. Numerous affidavits from family, friends, and colleagues attest to her character and capacity”. None of these witnesses were required for cross-examination. These affidavits demonstrate the strong support system available to the mother in Japan that she does not have in Australia. The mother asserts that the child is aware of and enjoys engaging with members of the maternal family via video and telephone calls.
The Court notes that the child has had limited physical, in person, contact with members of the mother’s family. This is an unfortunate byproduct of the lasting travel restrictions imposed upon the mother and the child, various illnesses of the mother and members of the mother’s family, and the present proceedings.
On balance the child’s ties to the parents’ families weighs slightly in favour of relocation and demonstrates the strong support system readily available to her in Japan.

Weight attributable to assertions of financial support by the father

One significant factor the mother suggests would warrant this Court allowing her to relocate with the child to Japan is her financial circumstances in Australia. It is an undeniable proposition that the financial wellbeing of a child’s main carer affects the standard of care and opportunities that they may be able to provide to a child.
In this matter, there are competing cross-allegations between the parents to the extent that the mother asserts that the father has been non-compliant or tardy in his support payments and the father asserts that the mother has been deliberately sabotaging her own financial wellbeing in order to induce this Court into allowing international relocation where it might not have otherwise done so.
It is uncontentious that the mother relies on social support and on support payments from the father to provide for herself and for the child. The father’s spousal support obligations towards the mother will only last until June 2026 (father’s written submissions, page 6). Thereafter, the mother would be reliant only on child support from the father, any continued Centrelink Special Benefit payments (if the mother’s review application is allowed) and any employment remuneration that she can source. The mother’s likely expenditure would include accommodation, childcare/schooling, further medical expenses associated with surgical procedures and recovery (mother’s written submissions, paragraph 13), alongside expenditure for general living and caring expenses. The mother has no real property in Australia and is currently reliant on social housing.
It is not in dispute that the mother technically can work in Australia, but given the mother’s English language deficits, the Court finds that the mother would be better positioned to find gainful employment should she return to Japan. The Court dismisses any allegation that the mother was working and hiding this from the father and the Court. Having made the allegation, the father bore the onus of proof in persuading the Court as to this fact. The evidence proffered by the father was not persuasive. It is entirely reasonable for the mother to volunteer at a business with other Japanese speaking individuals to foster a sense of community. Such desire to reach out and make connections with other Japanese nationals is entirely consistent with the other evidence before this Court. Just because the mother was in a place of work, does not mean she was in that place doing remunerated work.
Similarly, the Court dismisses any contention that the mother is preventing herself from working because of her medical conditions. Whilst it would no doubt be of great frustration to the father that the mother is still largely being supported by payments from him, and from social security payments in varying forms, it would be inappropriate to criticise the mother for refusing invasive surgery in a country where she feels vulnerable and has no direct familial support.
This Court dismisses the mother’s allegation that the father has consistently and deliberately failed to provide child support to the mother. Exhibit A18 details payments made to the mother. The Court accepts that, for the most part, the father has consistently paid child support to the mother albeit sometimes late.
Finally, the Court dismisses the father’s contention that the mother has deliberately sabotaged her financial wellbeing in aide of her case. The evidence does not establish this. It was a provocative, ill-considered submission to make.
The Court views that this factor weighs in favour of the mother relocating to Japan.

Communication between the parents

Communication between the parents will be of the utmost importance if the Court determines to allow the mother’s international relocation application, and even if it does not it is highly relevant to the competing applications between the parents as to decision making responsibility for major long-term issues.
The father contends that the parents have very good communication:
This has been confirmed by the Mother in cross-examination (*but for a suggestion that there was abusive written communication by the Father which she had decided not to put in her affidavit), by her concessions that the parents communicate in writing use the parenting application, face-to-face at changeovers, psychologist sessions and family ‘fun-days’ such as trips to restaurants for the Mother’s birthday and a day in Hyde Park flying a kite.

(father’s written submissions, page one)
The father’s assertion is largely correct. It appears that the parent’s communication was tense, fraught, and strained for most of these proceedings. There were numerous mutual allegations about conduct that may have undertaken to deliberately frustrate the other, allegations by the father that the mother was exaggerating various negative components of her own, and the child’s, welfare, and numerous police reports made by the mother against the father. All of these would have inevitably strained the communications between the parents.
Notwithstanding this, the parents have communicated via a parenting app and have otherwise been able to use lawyers to communicate regarding more significant issues. It is undeniable that in the period immediately preceding the final hearing, there was a drastic improvement in the parent’s relationship and communication. The Independent Children’s Lawyer’s written submissions at paragraph 11 best communicates the dynamic as found by the Court:
Communication between the parents has been fraught in the past however recent evidence indicates that the parties have been using a parenting app with success and have had some joint “fun days” together with [the child].
The Court is therefore optimistic and finds that on the cessation of these proceedings with the innate stress that they bring, the parties will have sufficient ability to communicate to render international relocation, or shared decision-making responsibility for major long-term issues possible. The parents should continue to communicate in writing, include by use of a Parenting Application, as they are successfully doing now.

The parents’ physical and mental health

The Court has no significant concerns about the father’s physical or mental health. The focus lies with the mother’s conditions.
As foreshadowed above, the mother requires urgent surgery. The situation is best explained at paragraph 13 of the mother’s written submissions:
[Dr FF’s] report, supported by surgeon [Dr GG], recommends the procedure occur in Japan due to prior complications and the need for post-operative care. That care cannot be adequately provided in Australia, where she is socially isolated. Relocation ensures the mother receives necessary treatment and family assistance, directly improving her parenting capacity.
The mother provided two exhibits that go to the status of her medical condition. Exhibit R3 is a medical certificate from BB Clinic in Japan. The certificate confirms that the mother is required to have surgery “to confirm whether [a] polyp has recurred or become cancerous” and that “as the bleeding at the resection site was observed the day after this surgery, and the haemostasis was performed, it would be desirable for the next examination to be conducted in an environment where the patient can be supported by her family”.
Exhibit R4 is a specialist report from the CC Hospital which confirms the content of Exhibit R3 “colonoscopy is an urgent investigation to make sure she does not have bowel cancer”, “she urgently requires a colonoscopy...” and “the best option for her may be to return to Japan to facilitate this procedure, as her child will need care whilst she has the procedure and in case of post procedural bleeding requiring prolonged hospitalisation...”. The recommendations for the mother to return to Japan are well founded but are not dispositive of any relocation application. Clearly, the mother has pressing medical issues that would benefit from occurring in Japan due to familial assistance in the recovery phase.
The mother also suggests that her mental health has suffered as a result of these proceedings. In support of this proposition, she caused the affidavit of Ms EE (“[Ms EE]”) to be filed on 21 July 2025 (“[Ms EE’s] affidavit”). Ms EE is a counsellor and registered psychologist and is thus qualified to give expert evidence on the state of the mother’s mental wellbeing.
At page six of Ms EE’s affidavit, it is recorded that as of 2025:
[The mother] still suffers from traits of depression, anxiety, as well as those that may resemble PTSD. Her overall symptoms fluctuate at times but generally continue to improve despite numerous stresses which she has been experiencing. During this period, Cognitive Behaviour Therapy (CBT) was used to target her depression and anxiety symptoms. In addition, Eye Movement Desensitisation Reprocessing (EMDR) was also used to alleviate PTSD symptoms.

Results for her most recent Depression Anxiety Stress Scale (DASS-21) and Posttraumatic Stress Scale-Civilian version (PCL-C) on 1/7/2025 were:

DASS-21:

Depression-Extremely Severe

Anxiety-Moderate

Stress-Mild

PCL-C: 42 (a score above 44 is indicative of possible PTSD)
Notably, compared to earlier results of the mother’s her stress and PTSD related scoring had improved, although remain distinctly high compared to the general population, but her “depression score has worsened as of late” (Ms EE’s affidavit, page six). Whilst based on the mother’s reports only, Ms EE’s affidavit also highlights various factors the mother considers to be impacting on her wellbeing. These include the prolonged legal proceedings, her ongoing physical health issues, her personal worry for the maternal grandmother’s wellbeing as she assertedly lives alone, and from the inability to see the maternal grandfather as he suffers from thrombosis and is unable to fly to Sydney (Ms EE’s affidavit, page six). The Court had no reason to doubt the veracity of this unchallenged evidence.
As admitted by the father in his written submissions, “The Father must make the concession that the Mother has been very consistent in her desire to return to Japan”. To some degree this acts as an implicit concession that the mother’s mental state would benefit from this Court permitting her to relocate to Japan with the child. If the mother is allowed to relocate, she will be the majority carer of the child. It is also not unreasonable to infer that improvement in the mother’s mental wellbeing, or psychological outlook, could only provide benefit to the child, directly or indirectly.
The Court finds that the mother’s physical and mental health conditions weight in favour of allowing her international relocation application.

Will the father’s relationship with the child be impacted by relocation

An important consideration is whether the Court is confident that relocation would not substantially affect the relationship between the father and the child. It was seemingly accepted by all parties that, by virtue of the increased geographic distance, the father and the child’s the relationship would change. This is self-evident. The focus is on how that change is likely to manifest, and if any negative manifestation of such change can be mitigated.
The father put his position simply at page six of his written submissions, “It is undeniable that the Child’s relationship with her father will be deeply affected if she relocates to Japan”. There is an implicit concession that his relationship will continue, and this is reflected in all proposals before the Court. The father’s relationship with the child has developed strongly since the commencement of overnight time (Exhibit R2). It does not follow, however, that the reconfiguration of his time would fail to continue a sound relationship with the father.
The Court accepts the submissions of the Independent Children’s Lawyer at page two of her written submissions:
The period of regular time with the father has enabled [the child] to develop a relationship and this will enable the child to maintain a relationship in the event relocation is permitted.
This is not about attachment (an early childhood clinical concept) as the father submits but rather the strengthening of the developing current relationship which mitigates any loss in the event of relocation.
...
It is the ICLs view that any risk diminishment of relationship with the father is outweighed by the risk to the child of a diminishment if the mother’s mental and physical health and standard of living if she were to remain in Australia.
The Court does not accept the firm views of the Single Joint Expert to the effect that international relocation would be ipso facto dangerous to the father’s relationship with the child. The Single Expert Report was based on interviews that took place on 28 November 2023, and much has happened since then in terms of the development of the father-child relationship. Indeed, in cross-examination the Single Joint Expert was much more sanguine about the father’s relationship with the child continuing after relocation.
The mother has consistently allowed the father to spend time with the child consistent with orders of this Court. Whilst the father is concerned that this would change, should relocation be permitted, that of itself does not predict non-compliance with orders. This Court has found that any orders it may make regarding time with the child are registrable in Japan by virtue of Article 118 and can be enforced using the mirror-orders procedure as described by Dr Dr DD. Further, on the father’s own evidence, the mother has shown a recent willingness to facilitate many “fun” activities between the father, herself and the child. This is a promising indicator for arrangements in Japan. The Court rejects the assertion that the mother was merely seeking to impress the Court by her cooperation and child-focus. Her actions are as consistent with not being permitted to relocate as being permitted to relocate.
Even though the Court has found that the mother suffered family violence at the hands of the father, she has facilitated the child’s time with the father. The Court agrees with the mother’s written submissions at page five, “this is powerful evidence of her commitment to supporting the father–child relationship despite trauma...”.
The Court has considered the history of the mother’s complaints to this Court and to the Police against the father. But for the trauma the mother likely experienced as a result of the assault by the father, the Court might have been somewhat critical of the path the mother chose to pursue many of the complaints. There are alternate explanations for her conduct, other than “police shopping” or inferred malign intention to punish, or jail, or to remove the child from the father’s care. The mother has done well to allow herself to move on from the 24 July 2021 incident. The progress of the mother can be seen in her gradually increasing ability to facilitate time between the child and the father. Indeed, the Court infers that the mother’s increased willingness to facilitate “fun” activities with the father, child and herself prior to the trial as symptomatic of the therapeutic work that she has undertaken.
The Court agrees with the Independent Children’s Lawyer at page two of her written submissions that the mother’s proposal is further evidence an intention by the mother to facilitate a relationship between the father and the child should this Court allow her relocation application:
The mother provides a plan to ensure the Father’s relationship with [the child] is maintained. She expressed to the Court that her relationship with her father was important to her and that she would want [the child] to have a good relationship with her father. She just wants [the child] to have stability and routine. her proposal is a gradual and considered one both here and if relocation is permitted. The Court would be satisfied that the mother is genuine in her desire to support a relationship with the father in circumstances where she is permitted to relocate or otherwise.
On balance, this factor weighs heavily in favour of allowing the mother’s international relocation application.

Father’s capacity to travel

A further weighty consideration for the Court as regards the mother’s international relocation application is the father’s physical and financial capacity to travel to Japan.
The father has adduced no evidence of any physical disabilities that would prevent him from traveling to Japan. Further, the father was at pains to emphasise to the Court at paragraph 52 of his affidavit filed 29 April 2024:
Additionally, I am in a strong position to provide for [the child] financially as well as provide for her day-to-day needs. The flexibility that I have with work allows me to fit in around the mother’s work commitments. I work from Sydney City and from home as necessary, depending on clients and my schedule. As an example, I am available each day to do [the child’s] school pick ups and drop offs as required.

Emphasis added
It is therefore apparent to the Court, on the father’s own evidence, that he is neither prevented by finances or scheduling from visiting the child in Japan, should he be given adequate notice.
The Court was not provided with any evidence as to the usual flight costs associated with a trip from Australia to Japan. Therefore, this Court may not take judicial notice of many of the facts contended that the Court ought to find by the mother at paragraph 35 of her written submissions. The Court, of course, does not deny the proposition that digital communication may assist the child and the father to remain in regular contact.
On balance, the Court finds that the father can travel to Japan should relocation be ordered, and therefore this factor weighs in favour of the mother’s relocation application.

Is the mother likely to impede the father’s access to the child following relocation

Notwithstanding all the findings of the Court above, international relocation should not be permitted if the mother intends to impede the father’s access to the child once this Court’s jurisdiction has been exhausted. The father claims precisely this at page six of his written submissions:
the Mother’s conduct to date has lead him to the conclusion that she will not support his relationship with the Child in Japan and engage in systems abuse to restrict that time, if she is allowed to relocate.
Further, the father claims on a related note at pages three and four of his written submissions:
The Court will note that upon her return to Japan, the Mother will no longer have a documented history of Police Shopping. The Mother will have the advantage of being a native Japanese speaker and being somebody with a native understanding of the Japanese administrative and legal system. It would not be difficult to imagine a situation whereby the Mother, if dissatisfied by the Father’s behaviour during any time he might have with [the child] in Japan pursuant to orders of the Court, may make reports to Japanese police in a similar manner.

Emphasis in original
The father’s criticism of the mother’s conduct is devoid of context, particularly the fact of his violent assault on her, and the likely traumatic impact on the mother. She was clearly fearful for her safety. She was, based on her own evidence, likely hypervigilant. The central contention of the father, that the mother was engaged in “police shopping” gains an entirely different complexion in context. To suggest, somehow, that this conduct would continue on relocation home to Japan is baseless.
There is no evidence before this Court to support the father’s contention that after relocation the mother would seek to impede his relationship, and time with the child. The father’s contention is rejected.

Determination as to International Relocation

The father, with significant nuance, tells the Court at page nine of his written submissions, the following:
This case must ultimately turn on the value of [the child’s] relationship with her Dad versus the benefits to the Mother of being allowed to return to her Motherland. The Court must consider whether allowing the Mother to travel to Japan would be sufficient to improve the Mother’s experience of living in Australia, or, if relocation must occur, whether that relocation should be delayed so as to improve and ensure a secure attachment between [the child] or her Father.
The Independent Children’s Lawyer favours the prospect of the mother relocating with the child:
It is the ICLs view that any risk diminishment of relationship with the father is outweighed by the risk to the child of a diminishment if the mother’s mental and physical health and standard of living if she were to remain in Australia.

(Independent Children’s Lawyer’s written submissions, paragraph 21)
The Court has above found that there are alternate avenues for the father’s relationship for the child to be maintained, and, that it is incorrect to view the relationship between the child and the father as one requiring a focus on attachment. If the mother is to relocate to Japan, she will remain the primary carer for the child. The Court infers that more comfortable and supportive surroundings are likely to increase a parent’s capability to best care for a child. There is no evidence proffered in this case that would suggest that such a general principle is inapplicable to the mother. Therefore, this Court gives significant weight to the mother’s contention at paragraphs 16 and 17 of her written submissions:
In Japan, the mother would have stable housing with family, access to meaningful work, and financial security. Her improved circumstances directly enhance the child’s stability and wellbeing.

The mother is socially and emotionally isolated in Australia. She has struggled with depression and anxiety, conditions exacerbated by her circumstances here. In Japan, she will regain cultural belonging, professional identity, and familial support, all of which improve her parenting capacity.
Considering all matters above, and with broad regard to the factors listed in s 60CC of the Act, the Court finds that the mother’s relocation application ought to be allowed. The Court strongly weighs the fact that the mother, as the majority carer of the child, will likely be in a much better financial, psychical and emotional position following any relocation. The Court also very strongly weighs the fact that the father has the ability to travel to Japan to facilitate time with the child, and that modern video communication technology enables the child to have a relationship with the father even whilst he is not in Japan.

SUBSTANTIVE PARENTING ARRANGEMENTS

Having now determined that it is in the best interests of the child and the mother to allow international relocation to Japan, it is significantly simpler to resolve the substantive parenting arrangements between the parties.

When should the mother and the child be permitted to relocate

The father contends that the child should not be permitted to relocate to Japan until she turns seven years old.
The Independent Children’s Lawyer and the mother oppose any such restraint.
The Single Joint Expert in cross-examination seemed open to a delayed relocation but focussed on the benefits of the child being able to express her feelings about the changes she was experiencing as she grew older. The impact of the change to the child would be just as significant in a delayed relocation as with an immediate one. When the father’s solicitor-advocate suggested that relocation at age seven might work, he agreed provided travel to Japan in the meantime was agreed to. The Court notes that this formed no part of the father’s proposal. The answers of the Single Joint Expert points to the importance of the mother and child being able to return quickly to Japan.
The rationale for the father’s position is not clear to the Court. It is presumed that such a delay would be used as additional time to strengthen the relationship between the father and the child, and to give adequate time to prepare for the mother and child’s eventual relocation. If this is indeed the intended purpose, it is not accepted. The onus was on the father to show what benefit accrues to the child of delaying relocation. He failed to do so. The negative impact of the delay on the mother was not considered by the Single Joint Expert. On the totality of the evidence before the Court, the mother and child will benefit from the quickest relocation that is practicable. The Court needs only to be reasonably satisfied that its order is recognised and enforceable in Japan. Procedural orders will be made to facilitate this.
Until such time as the mother does permanently relocate with the child to Japan, the current interim parenting orders in force between the parents will remain.

Who shall the child live with

The father does not propose to relocate to Japan on a full-time basis, on this factor alone it would be impractical for him to have the child reside primarily with him. The child is well settled with the mother, and the mother is likely to have a far greater support network to assist with the care of the child after relocation. The child shall live with the mother and spend time with the father in accordance with the orders of this Court.

What time should the child spend with the father

School term time

The father does not propose structured regular time with the child during the school term upon relocation to Japan, only time in the school holiday periods. The highest the Court can take the father’s position is that his proposed Order 13 would allow for five nights of additional time with the child, when the father is in Japan, regardless of whether this is during school term time or not.
The mother’s position provides for school term time between the father and the child on an alternating weekly basis, that will increase after July 2026. From July 2026 onwards, this structure would see the father, when he is in Japan, spend school term time with the child from 3:30 pm on Friday to 3:30 Sunday in the first week, and from 3:30 pm Tuesday to 8:30 am on Thursday in the second week. The child would thus be entitled to four overnight visits a fortnight with the father during the school term.
The Independent Children’s Lawyer contends for a less restrictive regime than the mother, however, such regime is optional and flexible in a manner more closely resembling the father’s proposal. Simply stated, the Independent Children’s Lawyer proposes the child to spend three nights a week with the father, when he is in Japan, during school term. Those three nights are to occur on an unfixed schedule. The Court infers that the exact timing of those three nights would be as agreed between the parties.
The primary purpose for the father’s time with the child in Japan is to facilitate the continuation of the relationship he currently has the child. In the Court’s view this would be best achieved by the mother’s proposed orders. If the Court were to make orders in the form suggested by either the father or the Independent Children’s Lawyer, there would be an innate level of unpredictability to any arrangement. It would require further communication between the parents and potentially disturb any extra-curricular activities the child is involved in on the days they are now spending time with the father on.
The mother’s structured proposal allows for the child to have a stable routine with known windows for potential disruption. It is envisioned that the father, if only in Japan for one week, would be entitled to time in accordance with the first alternate week schedule, and if he stayed for two or more weeks, would be entitled to the time as per the reciprocal alternating week schedule.

Time during the School Holidays

Holiday time between the father and the child is, perhaps, the most crucial element of the parents’ proposal for the Court to determine, insofar as maintenance of the child’s relationship with the father is concerned.
The father suggests that the Court should order the child to spend time with him for the entirety of four-week Japanese summer school holidays, in the Commonwealth of Australia, if he elects, and for a further two-week block during the Australian summer school holiday period potentially including the Christmas period.
The mother seeks two separate regimes, one for when the father is to spend time with the child in Japan, the other when the child spends time with the father in the Commonwealth of Australia. When the father is in Japan during the Japanese school holidays, she seeks a gradually increasing regime of time, beginning with two nights a piece between the mother and the father prior to July 2026, up to the entirety of the school holidays from January 2032. Should the father not decide to travel to Japan, the mother seeks the child to spend time in the Commonwealth of Australia in the same gradually progressing regime outlined above during the Japanese summer school holidays in odd numbered years, and during even numbered years during the Australian spring summer holidays and the Japanese winter school holidays.
The Independent Children’s Lawyer supported the mother’s regime.
The Court understands why the father formatted his orders in the manner he did. He wished to have the most time with the child possible, and for such time to be largely autonomous of the mother. Unfortunately, this is not the most appropriate path forward for the child. Notwithstanding the child’s existing relationship with the father, it would be disruptive for the child to spend up to four weeks at a time with the father, without seeing the mother. The mother is the current primary carer of the child. At present the child spends no more than four nights a fortnight with the father according to the Orders of this Court dated 18 February 2025. There is no indication that the child is psychologically or emotionally ready for such a significant departure from the established routine. Further, there is no basis for the father to effectively have first option over Christmas time with the child every single year. This is inherently unfair and unprecedented.
The Court favours the mother’s proposal. It provides time for the child to get adjusted to her new surroundings. The gradually increasing regime allows for the development of an anchor point with the mother, whilst also allowing as time progresses for significant and substantial time with the father. Further, the mother’s proposal for time between the father and the child in the Commonwealth of Australia is significant. It also provides a distinct mark of convenience for the father in receiving time with the child spread out across the year, in the event that he is unable to travel to Japan for some future unprecedented reason.

Special occasion time

If the Court allowed the mother and the child to relocate to Japan, the father did not seek any specific special occasion time. The Court infers this may be the reason behind why the father sought Christmas with the child every year to the exclusion of the mother. This being recognised, the Court acknowledged that special occasion time is still important to the father.
The mother’s proposal provides for in person time between the child and the father on certain special occasions, if the father is in Japan at the time, or otherwise time between the father and the child via video call on the day of the special occasion.
The Independent Children’s Lawyer largely supports the mother’s proposal, however her position does not provide for video calls between the child and the father on the day of identified special occasions in the event the father is not in Japan.
The Court views that the mother’s proposal should be made. It is inherently fair and equitable between the parents. It’s innate flexibility in the mode of time able to be spent between the father and child is desirable should the father ever be prevented from travelling to Japan for a substantial period of time. As mentioned above, it is clear the father would derive some benefit from special occasion time, and this would give him the ability to receive that, despite his initial proposal.

How will decision making responsibility be allocated

The Court gives minimal weight to the father’s proposal that he be afforded any determinative say in major long-term decisions regarding the child. The mother will be the child’s primary carer and thus is immensely more likely to be in a positive to proactively engage with issues that emerge going forward.
This does not mean that the father should have no say in what decisions are made for the child. Extensive judicial experience informs the Court that a plethora of benefits flow to a child when they know that both parents are engaged in their lives. The recent improvement in communication and attitude between the parents gives the Court comfort that such interaction can occur via email, text message, parenting application, or some other trackable written form.
Orders shall be made that provide for the mother to consult with the father before making any non-urgent decision regarding the child.
Further orders shall be made obliging the parents to provide such consents and authorities as may be required to the child’s schools and medical treaters to furnish both parents with information about the child’s welfare and progression. Without this information, the consultation between the father and the mother will only pay lip service to the idea of active involvement by the father in the child’s life. He needs to know all relevant background information on an issue he is consulted about in order to provide meaningful rebuttal or agreement.

What information should be shared between the parents

Given the geographic distance between the parents, information must be exchanged between them. The information exchanged is no doubt informed by the allocation of parental responsibility. That is not to say, however, that merely because the father does not have a determinative say about major long-term decisions about the child, he is not to receive nor provide information.
The Court views that the parents would be best served by providing each other with their current residential address, email address, and a current telephone number on which they can be contacted. To ensure that this does not become redundant at a later point, the parents shall advise one another of any changes to their contact details as soon as practicable thereafter, or in any instance within seven days of such change.
In addition to any regular communication between the parents, it is inherently fair and equitable for the parent with whom the child is currently spending time with informs the other, in the event of emergency, any medical problems or illnesses suffered by the child and any medication prescribed for the child as a result of such maladies.

Watchlist and passport orders

The child is currently on the Family Law Watchlist and is thus prevented from leaving the Commonwealth of Australia. As the Court will allow the relocation back to Japan, this order is no longer necessary.
Given that the mother is the primary carer of the child, she should hold the child’s passport at all material times. By extension of this, the mother shall be deemed to have all necessary power and be vested with the right to sign all necessary authority to ensure that the child has, and maintains, a Japanese and an Australian passport, if possible.
In addition to the mother paying all costs associate with her and the child’s relocation to Japan, it is equitable for the father to pay for the mother’s and child’s travel to Australia when the child resides in Japan, and for the mother to pay for all of the child’s travel expense to Japan whilst the child resides in Australia.

Orders for registration of these Orders in the Kyoto Family Court, and consent orders

The Court earlier found within these reasons for judgment that the Japanese family law system would recognise orders made by this Court but that enforceability and recognition require separate processes to achieve. There is no reason to doubt that both can and will be achieved by ordering the mother in the circumstances of this case.
The Court views it appropriate to adopt the proposal agreed between the mother and the Independent Children’s Lawyer that would oblige the father to do all things necessary to acquire and provide to the mother all documents required to register him as the father of the child in Japan, appoint legal representatives in Japan, and to undertake whatever process may be required to homologise and register Mirror Orders or Consent Orders with the Family Court of Kyoto which reflects the child’s time with each parent as per these Orders.

Restraints

The Independent Children’s Lawyer seeks that a number of restraints be imposed by this Court. The restraints prevent the parents from exposing the child to violence, whether such threats or intimidation or violence be directed at the child or any other person, from denigrating the other parent, or a member of that parent’s family, and, from physically discipling the child, causing or allowing any third person from doing so.
The Court notes that certain allegations were raised about the father’s conduct in disciplining the child (mother’s affidavit filed 21 July 2025, paragraph 8(a)). The Court does not have sufficient evidence to make any definitive findings on the veracity of these allegations. In these circumstances, the Court views that it is prudent to make the restraints suggested by the Independent Children’s Lawyer. They are protective, equitable; insofar as they apply to both parents equally and minimally impede any lawful actions the parents may take.

Ancillary orders in the best interest of the child

Various ancillary orders have been made by the Court, with the explanation for these outlined below.

Counselling

Acknowledging this Court’s findings that the child has been exposed to family violence, and noting the recommendations of the child’s current educators, the child should continue receiving counselling, or other psychological intervention. The Court does not accept the father’s contentions, express or otherwise, that Ms Q is an inappropriate person for the child to be attending upon whilst the child remains in the Commonwealth of Australia. The Court views that the child should continue to receive some form of counselling following her relocation to Japan, both for the aforementioned exposure to family violence, and also for general remedial benefit associated with the stresses of relocation. The mother shall ensure that the child attend upon a similarly suitably qualified mental health practitioner during her time in Japan.

Schooling

The Court views it as being appropriate to codify elements of the mother that oblige her, upon arriving in Japan to do all things and acts necessary to effect the child’s timely enrolment at either T Daycare (or a similar day care with an English language program), or S School (or a similar after school English Language program). In the interim, whilst the child remains in the Commonwealth of Australia, the mother ought to pay for the child’s Japanese School. Similarly, upon the child’s relocation the mother should pay for the child’s English School.

Updates

The Court finds that the mother’s proposal to update the father on a monthly basis via Time Tree App when the child is otherwise not spending time the father during that calendar month is appropriate in tenor but does not go far enough. The father is concerned about the deterioration of his relationship with the child. It is inarguable that he will have less opportunity to physically see and spend time with the child than he does now. It is appropriate for the father to receive an update from the mother at the beginning of each calendar month, or other such date as agreed between the parents in writing, via the Time Tree App (or any other such parenting application as agreed between the parents in writing), when the child is not otherwise scheduled to spend time with the father during that calendar month.
Such communication is to be fulsome and must include a description of the child’s highlights for the month, any co-curricular activities completed, update of schooling progress, and at least one photo of the child. It is only upon including this additional information that the Court feels that the father can be appropriately considered to have received a true “update” about how the child is progressing.

Videocalls

One of the factors that the Court weighed heavily in its consideration of whether to allow the mother to relocate to Japan with the child was the availability and ease of international communication via modern video communication tools and software. It is therefore necessary for the Court to prescribe an arrangement that allows the father to receive ongoing and meaningful video communication with the child.
The Court views that the mother’s proposal for electronic communication is largely appropriate and will be made with minor variations. The largest of such deviation includes additional procedural processes for the father to request communication on following days in the event that scheduled video communication cannot occur for whatever reason.

ORDERS IN THE BEST INTERESTS OF THE CHILDREN

Having regard to the totality of the evidence before the Court, the orders made are in the best interests of the child.
